Mexico Oil Firm Pemex Creates Cogeneration Unit, Shuffles Executives


Posted on May 26, 2015


After losing it’s title as Mexico’s oil producer, Pemex is now exploring the option of producing electricity. The company is restructuring and creating a Cogeneration and Services division which will harness excess of vapor and heat form its industrial operations.
by Lawrence Iliff, Wall Street Journal, May 22nd, 2015
National oil company Petróleos Mexicanos created a cogeneration unit for electricity production during a meeting of its board of directors Friday, and shuffled executives at its restructured exploration and production unit, the company said.
The new Pemex Cogeneration and Services division will oversee the harnessing of excess vapor and heat from the oil firm’s industrial operations—especially at refineries—to produce electricity for sale.
An energy overhaul last year ended Pemex’s monopoly on oil production while also opening up the electricity sector, which has been dominated by the state utility Comision Federal de Electricidad. In wake of the reform, Pemex plans to go from being the nation’s biggest electricity consumer to becoming a net producer, the company has said.
The Pemex board named Eleazar Gomez Zapata as director of the cogeneration unit. He previously served as the maintenance coordinator at the corporate operations unit.
The oil company’s board also voted to restructure its exploration and production unit as the company prepares to compete with private players. Rather than having one director named by the nation’s president, as was standard practice for decades, Pemex will now have a three-person committee to divide up those duties, with the executives named by the board.
Former exploration and production chief Gustavo Hernandez was named operations director of the committee. Juan Javier Hinojosa was named production director and Jose Antonio Escalera will be the exploration chief, Pemex said in a news release.



Tags: electricity production, Mexico, Mexico energy reform, oil production, Pemex







 

